---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Coordinate Transformations">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/mathematics">Mathematics</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>Coordinate Transformations</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Mathematics · Article 5 of 5</span>
        <h1>Coordinate Transformations</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          GNSS receivers output latitude, longitude and height. Algorithms work in ECEF Cartesian.
          Sensors report in body frame. Maps use local projections. Moving between these coordinate
          systems — correctly and efficiently — requires rotation matrices, Euler angles,
          quaternions and datum transformations. This article covers the mathematics you need.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>12 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#rotation-matrices">Rotation matrices</a></li>
          <li><a href="#euler-angles">Euler angles</a></li>
          <li><a href="#gimbal-lock">Gimbal lock</a></li>
          <li><a href="#quaternions">Quaternions</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ecef-enu">ECEF to ENU</a></li>
          <li><a href="#geodetic-ecef">Geodetic to ECEF and back</a></li>
          <li><a href="#helmert">Helmert datum transformation</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="rotation-matrices">Rotation matrices</h2>
      <p>
        A rotation matrix R rotates a vector from one coordinate frame to another while
        preserving its length. Rotation matrices are orthogonal — their inverse equals
        their transpose:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">R ∈ SO(3):   RᵀR = I,   det(R) = +1</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          SO(3) = Special Orthogonal group in 3D — the set of all valid rotation matrices.
          The +1 determinant distinguishes proper rotations from reflections (which have det = −1).
          Orthogonality means R⁻¹ = Rᵀ — inverting a rotation is free (just transpose).
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The three elementary rotation matrices about the x, y and z axes by angle θ are:
      </p>

      <div class="rotation-matrices">
        <div class="rm-card">
          <div class="rm-title">R_x(θ) — roll</div>
          <div class="rm-matrix">
            <div class="rm-row"><span>1</span><span>0</span><span>0</span></div>
            <div class="rm-row"><span>0</span><span>cos θ</span><span>−sin θ</span></div>
            <div class="rm-row"><span>0</span><span>sin θ</span><span>cos θ</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="rm-note">Rotation about x-axis. Positive θ = right-hand rule (right thumb along +x, fingers curl from +y to +z).</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rm-card">
          <div class="rm-title">R_y(θ) — pitch</div>
          <div class="rm-matrix">
            <div class="rm-row"><span>cos θ</span><span>0</span><span>sin θ</span></div>
            <div class="rm-row"><span>0</span><span>1</span><span>0</span></div>
            <div class="rm-row"><span>−sin θ</span><span>0</span><span>cos θ</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="rm-note">Note the sign pattern is different from R_x and R_z — a common source of errors. The sin θ in position (1,3) is positive.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rm-card">
          <div class="rm-title">R_z(θ) — yaw/heading</div>
          <div class="rm-matrix">
            <div class="rm-row"><span>cos θ</span><span>−sin θ</span><span>0</span></div>
            <div class="rm-row"><span>sin θ</span><span>cos θ</span><span>0</span></div>
            <div class="rm-row"><span>0</span><span>0</span><span>1</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="rm-note">Rotation about z-axis. Most common in navigation — heading (yaw) is a rotation about the vertical axis.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        To transform a vector v from frame A to frame B:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">v_B = R_BA · v_A</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          R_BA = rotation matrix that takes vectors expressed in A and expresses them in B.
          Convention matters: R_BA means "from A to B". Some texts use the opposite convention —
          always check which way the matrix transforms before using it.
          To go from B back to A: v_A = R_BAᵀ · v_B = R_AB · v_B.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="euler-angles">Euler angles</h2>
      <p>
        Any 3D rotation can be parameterised by three Euler angles. In navigation, the most
        common convention is <strong>ZYX (yaw-pitch-roll)</strong> — also called
        aerospace or Tait-Bryan angles:
      </p>

      <div class="euler-def">
        <div class="euler-angle">
          <div class="ea-symbol">ψ</div>
          <div class="ea-name">Yaw (heading)</div>
          <div class="ea-desc">Rotation about body z-axis. 0° = north, positive = clockwise when viewed from above. Range: −180° to +180°.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="euler-angle">
          <div class="ea-symbol">θ</div>
          <div class="ea-name">Pitch</div>
          <div class="ea-desc">Rotation about (intermediate) y-axis. Positive = nose up. Range: −90° to +90°. Singularity at ±90°.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="euler-angle">
          <div class="ea-symbol">φ</div>
          <div class="ea-name">Roll</div>
          <div class="ea-desc">Rotation about (new) x-axis. Positive = right wing down. Range: −180° to +180°.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The combined rotation matrix from body frame to navigation frame (NED) is:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">R_nb = R_z(ψ) · R_y(θ) · R_x(φ)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          Applied right to left: first roll (φ), then pitch (θ), then yaw (ψ).
          Order matters — matrix multiplication is not commutative.
          R_z(ψ) · R_y(θ) · R_x(φ) gives a different rotation than R_x(φ) · R_y(θ) · R_z(ψ).
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Expanding the product gives the Direction Cosine Matrix (DCM):
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">R_nb = ⎡cψcθ   cψsθsφ−sψcφ   cψsθcφ+sψsφ⎤</div>
        <div class="formula">       ⎢sψcθ   sψsθsφ+cψcφ   sψsθcφ−cψsφ⎥</div>
        <div class="formula">       ⎣−sθ    cθsφ           cθcφ        ⎦</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          c = cos, s = sin. Subscripts dropped for brevity (cψ = cos ψ, etc.).
          This 9-element matrix is how aircraft, ships and INS systems represent attitude
          in real-time computations. It can be updated by: Ṙ = R · Ω (where Ω is the
          skew-symmetric matrix of angular rate from the gyroscope).
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="gimbal-lock">Gimbal lock</h2>
      <p>
        Euler angles have a fundamental problem: when pitch θ = ±90°, the yaw and roll axes
        become aligned and one degree of freedom is lost. This is <strong>gimbal lock</strong>.
        Mathematically, the Jacobian that maps Euler angle rates to angular velocities
        becomes singular:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">⎡φ̇⎤   ⎡1  sin φ tan θ   cos φ tan θ⎤⁻¹   ⎡ωₓ⎤</div>
        <div class="formula">⎢θ̇⎥ = ⎢0  cos φ         −sin φ       ⎥    ⎢ω_y⎥</div>
        <div class="formula">⎣ψ̇⎦   ⎣0  sin φ/cos θ   cos φ/cos θ ⎦    ⎣ω_z⎦</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          The 1/cos θ terms blow up at θ = ±90°. For aircraft this is rarely a problem
          (planes don't fly vertically), but for spacecraft, missiles and manoeuvring vehicles
          it is critical. Quaternions solve this completely.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="quaternions">Quaternions</h2>
      <p>
        A unit quaternion represents a 3D rotation using 4 numbers — no singularity, efficient
        computation, and smooth interpolation. A quaternion is:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">q = q₀ + q₁i + q₂j + q₃k = [q₀, q⃗],   q⃗ = [q₁, q₂, q₃]ᵀ</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          q₀ = scalar part (cos(θ/2)) · q⃗ = vector part (sin(θ/2) · û)<br/>
          û = unit rotation axis · θ = rotation angle<br/>
          Unit constraint: q₀² + q₁² + q₂² + q₃² = 1<br/>
          i² = j² = k² = ijk = −1 (quaternion algebra rules)
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        To rotate a vector v using quaternion q:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">v' = q ⊗ [0, v] ⊗ q*</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          q* = conjugate = [q₀, −q⃗] (inverse rotation for unit quaternion)<br/>
          ⊗ = quaternion multiplication (Hamilton product)<br/>
          The result [0, v'] extracts the rotated vector from the quaternion product.<br/><br/>
          Equivalent rotation matrix from quaternion:
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">R = ⎡q₀²+q₁²−q₂²−q₃²   2(q₁q₂−q₀q₃)       2(q₁q₃+q₀q₂)    ⎤</div>
        <div class="formula">    ⎢2(q₁q₂+q₀q₃)       q₀²−q₁²+q₂²−q₃²   2(q₂q₃−q₀q₁)    ⎥</div>
        <div class="formula">    ⎣2(q₁q₃−q₀q₂)       2(q₂q₃+q₀q₁)       q₀²−q₁²−q₂²+q₃²⎦</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          This conversion is used when switching between quaternion attitude propagation
          (no gimbal lock) and rotation matrix operations (needed for most linear algebra).
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="quat-advantages">
        <div class="qa-card">
          <div class="qa-icon">✓</div>
          <div class="qa-title">No gimbal lock</div>
          <div class="qa-desc">Unit quaternions parameterise all orientations smoothly — no singularity at any attitude.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-card">
          <div class="qa-icon">✓</div>
          <div class="qa-title">Efficient computation</div>
          <div class="qa-desc">Quaternion multiplication: 16 multiplications, 12 additions. DCM update: 54 multiplications. Quaternions win at high update rates.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-card">
          <div class="qa-icon">✓</div>
          <div class="qa-title">Smooth interpolation</div>
          <div class="qa-desc">SLERP (Spherical Linear Interpolation) interpolates smoothly between orientations — essential for animation and attitude smoothing.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="qa-card">
          <div class="qa-icon">✗</div>
          <div class="qa-title">Double cover</div>
          <div class="qa-desc">q and −q represent the same rotation. This double cover can cause sign flips that must be handled (q₀ should be kept positive).</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="ecef-enu">ECEF to ENU</h2>
      <p>
        The most common transformation in GNSS is from ECEF (Earth-Centred Earth-Fixed)
        to ENU (East-North-Up) at a reference point (φ₀, λ₀). The rotation matrix
        R_ENU from ECEF to ENU is:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">R_ENU = ⎡    −sin λ₀          cos λ₀         0    ⎤</div>
        <div class="formula">        ⎢−sin φ₀ cos λ₀   −sin φ₀ sin λ₀   cos φ₀⎥</div>
        <div class="formula">        ⎣ cos φ₀ cos λ₀    cos φ₀ sin λ₀   sin φ₀⎦</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          To convert an ECEF position difference ΔX = [ΔX, ΔY, ΔZ]ᵀ to ENU:
          [ΔE, ΔN, ΔU]ᵀ = R_ENU · ΔX<br/><br/>
          Inverse (ENU → ECEF): ΔX = R_ENUᵀ · [ΔE, ΔN, ΔU]ᵀ<br/><br/>
          This matrix is also used to compute satellite azimuth and elevation from
          the ECEF satellite direction vector — project into ENU, then:
          el = atan2(U, √(E²+N²)), az = atan2(E, N) mod 360°
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🧭</div>
        <div>
          <strong>NED vs ENU:</strong> Navigation systems (aircraft, ships) often use
          NED (North-East-Down) instead of ENU. NED has z pointing down (into the Earth),
          matching the right-hand rule with positive z in the direction of gravity.
          The NED rotation matrix is the ENU matrix with rows 1 and 2 swapped and row 3 negated.
          Always check which convention your library uses before comparing results.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="geodetic-ecef">Geodetic to ECEF and back</h2>
      <p>
        Converting between (φ, λ, h) and (X, Y, Z) is covered in the
        <a href="/learn/fundamentals/coordinate-systems">Coordinate Systems article</a>.
        Here we focus on the matrix form used in algorithm implementations.
      </p>

      <h3>Forward: geodetic → ECEF</h3>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">N(φ) = a / √(1 − e²·sin²φ)      (prime vertical radius of curvature)</div>
        <div class="formula">X = (N + h) · cos φ · cos λ</div>
        <div class="formula">Y = (N + h) · cos φ · sin λ</div>
        <div class="formula">Z = (N(1 − e²) + h) · sin φ</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          a = 6,378,137.0 m (WGS84 semi-major axis)<br/>
          e² = 0.00669437999014 (WGS84 first eccentricity squared)<br/>
          φ = geodetic latitude (rad), λ = longitude (rad), h = ellipsoidal height (m)
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Inverse: ECEF → geodetic (Bowring iteration)</h3>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">p = √(X² + Y²)             (distance from Z-axis)</div>
        <div class="formula">λ = atan2(Y, X)             (longitude — exact, one step)</div>
        <div class="formula">φ₀ = atan2(Z, p·(1−e²))    (initial latitude estimate)</div>
        <div class="formula">iterate:  N  = a/√(1−e²·sin²φ)</div>
        <div class="formula">          φ  = atan2(Z + e²·N·sin φ, p)</div>
        <div class="formula">until convergence (2–3 iterations, then:)</div>
        <div class="formula">h = p/cos φ − N             (or use Z/sin φ − N(1−e²) near poles)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          Convergence criterion: |φₙ − φₙ₋₁| &lt; 10⁻¹² rad (sub-micrometre accuracy).
          Alternative closed-form: Zhu (1994) or Bowring (1985) give directly without iteration
          to millimetre accuracy. Most implementations use 3 fixed Bowring iterations.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="helmert">Helmert datum transformation</h2>
      <p>
        Moving between datums (e.g. WGS84 to OSGB36) requires accounting for differences
        in origin, scale and orientation. The 7-parameter Helmert (similarity) transformation
        is the standard model:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">X' = T + (1+s)·R·X</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          <strong>T</strong> = translation vector [T_x, T_y, T_z]ᵀ (metres)<br/>
          <strong>s</strong> = scale factor (dimensionless, often given in parts per million)<br/>
          <strong>R</strong> = rotation matrix (small angle approximation for geodetic datums):
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">R ≈ ⎡ 1    −R_z   R_y⎤</div>
        <div class="formula">    ⎢ R_z   1    −R_x⎥</div>
        <div class="formula">    ⎣−R_y   R_x   1  ⎦</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          R_x, R_y, R_z = rotations about x, y, z axes (radians — usually given in arcseconds,
          convert: 1 arcsecond = π/648000 radians ≈ 4.848×10⁻⁶ rad).<br/><br/>
          Small angle approximation is valid because geodetic datums differ by at most a few
          arcseconds of rotation. For larger rotations (IMU alignment), use the full rotation
          matrix or quaternion.
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>OSGB36 ↔ WGS84 example</h3>
      <div class="helmert-example">
        <div class="he-row he-header">
          <span>Parameter</span>
          <span>Value</span>
          <span>Units</span>
        </div>
        <div class="he-row">
          <span>T_x</span>
          <span class="he-val">−446.448</span>
          <span>m</span>
        </div>
        <div class="he-row">
          <span>T_y</span>
          <span class="he-val">+125.157</span>
          <span>m</span>
        </div>
        <div class="he-row">
          <span>T_z</span>
          <span class="he-val">−542.060</span>
          <span>m</span>
        </div>
        <div class="he-row">
          <span>R_x</span>
          <span class="he-val">+0.1502</span>
          <span>arcsec</span>
        </div>
        <div class="he-row">
          <span>R_y</span>
          <span class="he-val">+0.2470</span>
          <span>arcsec</span>
        </div>
        <div class="he-row">
          <span>R_z</span>
          <span class="he-val">+0.8421</span>
          <span>arcsec</span>
        </div>
        <div class="he-row">
          <span>s</span>
          <span class="he-val">−20.4894</span>
          <span>ppm</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>7-parameter is not enough for the UK:</strong> The OSGB36 datum is slightly
          distorted relative to WGS84 — a single 7-parameter transformation leaves residuals
          of up to 5 m. The Ordnance Survey publishes OSTN15, a national grid shift file that
          reduces this to sub-centimetre by applying local corrections across a 1 km grid.
          Always use OSTN15 for survey work in the UK.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 — SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔄</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Rotation matrices</div>
          <div class="summary-body">R ∈ SO(3): orthogonal, det = +1, inverse = transpose. Elementary rotations R_x, R_y, R_z compose by matrix multiplication — order matters.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">✈️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Euler angles — intuitive but singular</div>
          <div class="summary-body">ZYX (yaw-pitch-roll) is standard in navigation. Gimbal lock at pitch = ±90°. Fine for typical flight and marine applications; use quaternions for full-sphere manoeuvring.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔢</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Quaternions — no singularity</div>
          <div class="summary-body">4-parameter unit quaternion, no gimbal lock, efficient multiplication. Standard in INS and robotics. Convert to/from rotation matrix when needed for linear algebra.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🌐</div>
          <div class="summary-title">ECEF ↔ ENU ↔ geodetic</div>
          <div class="summary-body">R_ENU rotates ECEF differences to local East-North-Up. Geodetic ↔ ECEF via Bowring iteration (3 steps). Datum shifts via 7-parameter Helmert + grid correction files.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section complete -->
      <div class="section-complete">
        <div class="complete-icon">✅</div>
        <div>
          <div class="complete-title">Mathematics section complete</div>
          <div class="complete-body">
            You now understand the algorithms that run inside every GNSS positioning engine —
            from least squares through Kalman filtering and integer ambiguity resolution to
            the coordinate transformations that tie it all together.
            One section remaining: Timing.
          </div>
          <a href="/learn/timing" class="complete-link">Continue to Timing →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/mathematics/ionospheric-models" class="nav-prev">← Ionospheric Models</a>
        <a href="/learn/timing" class="nav-next">Timing →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Groves, P. D. (2013). <em>Principles of GNSS, Inertial, and Multisensor Integrated Navigation Systems</em>, 2nd ed. Artech House. Appendix A–C.</li>
          <li>Kuipers, J. B. (1999). <em>Quaternions and Rotation Sequences</em>. Princeton University Press.</li>
          <li>Bowring, B. R. (1985). The geodesic line and short distances on the surface of an ellipsoid. <em>Survey Review</em>, 28(218), 202–219.</li>
          <li>Ordnance Survey (2015). A guide to coordinate systems in Great Britain (OSTN15/OSGM15). <a href="https://www.ordnancesurvey.co.uk/documents/resources/guide-coordinate-systems-great-britain.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">OS →</a></li>
          <li>Hofmann-Wellenhof, B., Lichtenegger, H. & Wasle, E. (2008). <em>GNSS — Global Navigation Satellite Systems</em>. Springer. Chapter 3.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

